<td class="" style="line-height:1.3em; vertical-align:middle;"><i><a href="/wiki/Aeolipile" title="Aeolipile">aeolipile</a></i></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Hero</b> (or <b>Heron</b>) <b>of Alexandria</b> (<a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title="Greek language">Greek</a>: <span lang="el" xml:lang="el"><b>Ἥρων ὁ Ἀλεξανδρεύς</b></span>) (c. 10–70 AD). was an ancient <a href="/wiki/Greek_mathematics" title="Greek mathematics">Greek mathematician</a> who was a resident of a Roman province (<a href="/wiki/Ptolemaic_Egypt" title="Ptolemaic Egypt" class="mw-redirect">Ptolemaic Egypt</a>); he was also an <a href="/wiki/Engineer" title="Engineer">engineer</a> who was active in his hometown of <a href="/wiki/Alexandria" title="Alexandria">Alexandria</a>. He is considered the greatest experimenter of antiquity<sup id="cite_ref-Dictionary_of_Scientific_Biography_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dictionary_of_Scientific_Biography-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and his work is representative of the <a href="/wiki/Hellenistic_civilization" title="Hellenistic civilization">Hellenistic</a> scientific tradition.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Among his most famous inventions were the first documented <a href="/wiki/Steam_engine" title="Steam engine">steam-powered device</a>, the <i><a href="/wiki/Aeolipile" title="Aeolipile">aeolipile</a></i>, and a <a href="/wiki/Windmill" title="Windmill">windwheel</a>, constituting one of the earliest instances of wind harnessing.<sup id="cite_ref-Drachmann_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Drachmann-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Lohrmann_10f._3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lohrmann_10f.-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> He is said to have been a follower of the <a href="/wiki/Atomism" title="Atomism">Atomists</a>. Some of his ideas were derived from the works of <a href="/wiki/Ctesibius" title="Ctesibius">Ctesibius</a>.</p>
